item.title: Hong Kong Teachers Fired and Afraid as China Targets Liberal Thinkers
item.description: Hong Kong teachers who backed antigovernment protests are being reprimanded and, in some cases, fired as China’s Communist Party moves to stamp out dissent. Observers fear the city’s tradition of liberal-education thinking will be supplanted by Chinese-style suppression of political discourse.

item.title: Bone-Dry Australia Faces Backlash Against Dam Projects
item.description: Australia’s plans for dam projects are angering some indigenous groups and alarming environmental activists who argue the dams will harm ecosystems and disturb cultural sites.

item.title: Netanyahu's Corruption Trial Resumes
item.description: An Israeli court ruled it would begin hearing testimony from witnesses in Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu’s corruption trial in January, drawing into focus the embattled leader’s challenges as he faces rising public anger over the government’s handling of the coronavirus crisis.

item.title: EU Talks on Economic Recovery Aid to Enter Third Day
item.description: Major differences remained on the amount of grants that would be handed out to struggling national governments as part of an economic recovery fund.

item.title: Tens of Thousands March in Russia's Far East, Defying Kremlin
item.description: Tens of thousands of people in Russia’s Far East marched in protests triggered by the arrest of a popular regional governor, but that have since morphed into a wave of growing dissatisfaction over social issues and the rule of President Vladimir Putin.

item.title: Travel Is Bouncing Back, but Tourists Stick Close to Home
item.description: In many parts of the world, travelers are out and about again. But they are staying largely in their own countries, driving a welcomed rebound in tourism as few have the ability to venture off to faraway destinations.
